title: Nantucket Field Station
equity_comment:
This month, the Grace Grossman Youth Collaborative, a program of the University of Massachusetts Boston Nantucket Field Station, received the 2012 Human Diversity Award from the Organization of Biological Field Stations, an association that supports the work of more than 200 biological field stations and marine laboratories around the world.

 The recognition includes an opportunity for Sarah Oktay, director of the Nantucket Field Station, to share information about the youth collaborative at the annual OBFS meeting in September, as well as reimbursement for the cost of attending the meeting.

 In granting the Human Diversity Award, The OBFS team cited the Grossman Youth Collaborative for serving urban schools throughout Massachusetts which provides high-school and middle-school students with a weeklong, expenses-paid trip to Nantucket. 

 "We are thrilled to receive the 2012 OBFS Human Diversity Award," Oktay said. "The youth program is very special. Many of the kids who come here have only experienced their own urban environments. To be able to introduce them to the ocean, to Nantucket's natural beauty, and even to a clear night sky full of planets and stars is an honor for those of us involved in the collaborative."

title: Salem Point Neighborhood Vision and Action Plan
external_collaborator: Salem, North Shore Community Development Coalition
equity_comment: A key part of this project's engagement strategy includes holding meetings in the primary languages spoken by neighborhood residents, offering translation and interpretation, and the substantive involvement of youth leaders in the design and implementation of outreach strategies. The project was also overseen by an Advisory Committee that included neighborhood residents, business owners, and representatives from nonprofit organizations serving people who live and work int he Point. The project exceeded its equity-related benchmarks for participation: residents taking part in the game and in both public meetings were diverse by race/ethnicity, national origin, familial status, and age. Please refer to keypad polling data from the public meetings.

title: Orange Line Opportunity Corridor Project
equity_comment: This project aimed to serve as an advocacy tool in support of equitable transit-oriented development that connects residents who already live along the corridor with job opportunities along the corridor and profiles the importance of preserving affordable housing located along the corridor that is at risk of expiring. The project met its equity-related benchmarks of securing the attendance of over 50 community members at the final presentation of research findings. Attendees were diverse in terms of race/color and age and familial status. The project also resulted in a final convening of open space and trails connectivity advocates and workforce development advocates working in the four municipalities.

title: Subregional Priority Area Mapping - North Suburban Planning Council (NSPC) Subregion
Salem Point Commercial Corridor Revitalization Plan
equity_comment: The current population in the Point is 63% non-white, consisting of mostly Latino immigrants, consistent with its history as a welcoming community for new immigrants.  The demographic makeup contrasts with the City as a whole, which is 75% white. The median household Income in the Point is $38,635, 31% lower than the citywide figure of $56,203. Fifty-eight percent of renter households are housing cost-burdened.  Unemployment is a hallmark issue in the Point neighborhood where the unemployment rate is 11.6%, compared to 7.3% citywide. This Plan, which will focus on the Congress and lower Lafayette Street corridor, will identify areas with housing and economic redevelopment potential in the Point, a historically underserved neighborhood in the City of Salem. It may increase opportunities for immigrant owned small businesses and increase the overall vitality of the neighborhood. The outcomes of this project may directly impact people in protected classes including: national origin, familial status, age, and source of income.
